ANALYSIS OF THE ANTI-DRUG ABUSE ACT OF 1986
Drug abuse in the US has become a ‘war’ in which the government is looking to win. Richard Schroeder wrote in 1975 that “our efforts to control it [drug abuse] have become a patchwork of policies, strategies and law.”1 What has followed has been a myriad of laws since 1975 that have addressed some specific ‘thing’ that was occurring. The war on drugs has taken its toll on the country effecting almost (if not) all of society2. This societal woe led to Congress passing the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970. Comprehensive it was, and it was the go to legislation for how the US should respond to the “drug problem.” Sixteen years later to the day on October 27, 1986 the President Regan signed what became known as: PL# 99-570, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. This bill changed the way Americans viewed and dealt with drug abuse.
Drug abuse legislation was not new, however at the present moment of time (early October 1986) Congress was deadlocked on “legislation to combat drug trafficking and narcotics abuse”3 according to New York Times correspondent David Rosenbaum. Traction began in the early part of the 1980’s with some ‘A” list celebrities who were used to portray drug abuse (John DeLorean, John Belushi), as well as then First Lady Nancy Reagan coining the phrase ‘just say no’ at an Oakland, CA elementary school in 1982.4 With the death of Len Bias that thrust cocaine and subsequently crack into a household name, movement was coming. House Democratic leader Jim Wright [TX] stated “Congress needs to mount a comprehensive attack against this menace that has come more and more to threaten our youth.”5 According to the West Encyclopedia of Law “the war on drugs created a patchwork of anti-drug laws…which toughened penalties for drug violations involving cocaine, especially its smokeable derivative, crack…[which] imposed minimum sentences, even for first time offenders..[that] while greatly increasing the number of drug offenders in prison, the law provoked considerable controversy over its effect on minorities.”6
Agenda Building US policymaking follows one (or more) of six models of reasoning which drive either a Representative or a Senator to write and present a bill for consideration and PL 99-570 is no exception.7 1986 seemed to be the year of drug policy.8 As stated earlier, in
