June of 1986 College basketball star Len Bias died from what was determined to be a cocaine overdose. This was the impetus that congress needed that year. Tip O’Neill was calling for some kind of drug legislation….and quickly.9 Why this basketball player? As Dan Baum writes:
The national pastime notwithstanding, the Congress of the United States has long been devoted to basketball than to any other sport…this was especially true in 1986, when the NBA championship was held by the Celtics, home team of the formidable House Speaker, Tip O’Neill …[Bias was] Congress’ home town hero, the nation’s model for healthy young black manhood…[who was] cheated out of his contract with the Speaker’s championship hometown team, and the culprit was the most terrifying drug on the street.10
The 1980’s was the ‘decade of decadence’ as coined by the Rock group Motley Crűe. During this time cocaine was the drug of choice
among the rich whereas crack became the “drug of choice” within the urban poor, mostly due to the economic conditions of the country at the time.11 Reaction to Len Bias’ death throughout the general population, sports world, as well as the political arena had
everyone questioning drugs, drug use and abuse. President Reagan addressed the American people in hopes to quench some of the fears and questions by stating “the key to our anti-drug strategy [is] a national crusade against drugs, a sustained, relentless effort to rid America of this scourge by mobilizing every segment of our society against drug abuse.”12 Policy makers couldn’t help but to see
that the public opinion was calling for them to make some changes to how the system was working (or not). Representative Jim Wright (D- TX) saw this as a chance to capitalize on Tip O’Neill’s request for legislation (that was failing to gain traction in the Senate) and use it as a political chess move. He introduced it to the House on September 8, 1986.13
Wright was the House Democratic leader at the time and saw to gain a few assets towards his political career from spearheading this bill. The first was since reelection was on the horizon Wright would find himself in a position to run for and subsequently become Tip O’Neill’s successor as the Speaker of the House.14 Next, due to earlier drug trafficking laws the cocaine that
was being smuggled into the US through Florida was now, by the mid 80’s coming from Mexico across the US border; with Texas
