being primary.15 According to one study, by the mid 1980’s cocaine transshipment between Mexico and the US [through Texas] had reached an all time high.16 Another thing that Wright had to gain through this law was the introduction of the death penalty for drug related offenses.17 Combined with the fact that the Texas prison system was overcrowded with drug related convicts who were having gang/drug related warfare going on behind bars, and Texas was threatened with an 800,000 a day fine unless it fixed the issue, it is easy to see how the passing of the bill would begin the process of alleviating the over crowding.18 Armed with many reasons, Wright saw that he could gain increased stronghold for his political agenda by using – and swaying public opinion (system model policy) with the point that society is changing (incrementalist model) and roll it all up into a bill that would benefit himself as well as help the greater need in society.
Policy Formulation According to the Library of Congress, the House and the Senate went back and forth in the summer of 1986 with over 50 resolutions and a landmark 150 amendments (prior to law) that cumulated in the submittal of HR 5484, thus becoming PL 99-570.19 The hardest one being the inclusion of the death penalty for drug related offenses. This was a crucial piece for getting the bill signed as outlined by Representative George Gekas [R-PA] saying “We have as a society to hold the death penalty over the heads of those who would kill at random to make sure their enterprise [their drug syndicate] remains intact…the inclusion of the death penalty for those individuals who, as drug kingpins, will stop at nothing to further their enterprise is exactly what is required as weaponry in this war on drugs.”20 Jim Wright chimed in to say that the bill would provide “sure and swift punishment” for drug related criminals and even Tip O’Neill (who didn’t agree to the death penalty) stated “Our people who are bitterly opposed to the death penalty see the handwriting on the wall.”21
