There were 46 floor actions that took place cumulating in the bill becoming law.22 There were 12 committees and four subcommittees involved in formulating the bill.23 There were a few committees that didn’t seem like they would be utilized for a drug law, yet; most notably interested was the House Energy and Commerce Committee. At first glance this does not seem like a committee that needs input on drug abuse, however it encompasses many facets of the government such as oversight, health, the economy, and of course trade. That solidifies the reason why the bill was introduced by Wright – too many drug deals going through the border from Texas and Mexico. A second committee to note was the House Education and Labor committee. President Reagan when signing this bill into law made a statement to the fact that Education would be receiving $200 million dollars (of the $1.7 billion) for drug education.24 The remaining committees each had a critical hand in and reason to gain from partnering with and supporting the bill (Appendix).
The bill contained two critical elements that helped draw attention to it.25 The first was an unprecedented law against money laundering, the first of its kind. The second key element was that congress was voting to reinstate prison terms for first time offenders, a trend that went away since an early amendment to the 1970 Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970.
Policy Adoption HR 5484, after going through numerous amendments officially became PL# 99-570, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. 26 The bill was signed into law on October 27, 1986 by President Reagan. The floor votes in the House and the Senate were confirmed by voice votes (House: 392:16 and the Senate was 97:2 – considered ‘unanimous consent’). As noted earlier, the House primary sponsor was Representative James C. Wright Jr. (D-TX-12). The Senate primary sponsor was Bob Dole (D-KS). There were 301 cosponsors in the house. From the Senate Dole had 29 co-sponsors, which were part of the original Senate bill S.2878 that was the original amendment sent back to the House.27 The House agreed to the Senate amendments by answering back with an amendment (pursuant to HR 597, inserting the text of HR5729 (which referred the bill to a subcommittee on Forest, Family Farms, and Energy).28 The adoption if this bill was quicker that most at just over a month (September 8, 1986, signed October 27, 1986). President Reagan at
