Policy Implementation Policy Implementation and enforcement are a crucial piece on analyzing how effective laws are. PL 99-570 has had some minor amendments have occurred since its implementation yet still remains the central drug enforcement policy for the US. According to the Executive Office of the Presidentdrug abuse is among the top two problems that faces America.30 The Report goes on to say that the key to reducing drug abuse is to reduce drug supply, however quite often what is reciprocated with low supply is increased violence. From a general perspective what has been shown is that in 1987 the US spent 4.24 billion dollars in supply reduction causes and 10 years later doubled the amount to 8.97 billion.31 In 1987 marijuana use was 37% and cocaine and heroin use were at 13.9% whereas in 1997 marijuana use fell only to 31.6% cocaine and heroin use fell to 3.7%.32 According to Burrus’s article (231) the major outcomes of any drug policy “should be the reduction of drug consumption and the reduction of drug related harm.” According to the DEA, in 2006 there were 30,701 arrests made in conjunction with drug related charges (which fell in 2012 to 30,476) whereas in 1986 there were only 19,884 arrests made.33 The DEA has also kept statistics on the number of seizures of drugs. Referring to cocaine, heroin, methamphetamines, and marijuana, there has been an increase in the amount of seized drugs.34 These numbers pale in comparison to what the FBI records show. The FBI started collecting yearly stats in 1995, however in 1980 the number of arrests for all drug related issues was at 580,900 and skyrocketed to 1,552,432 in 2012.35 Drug Enforcement was also taken to a new level in 1988 with PL 100-690, the Drug Free Workplace Act of 1988. The key item from this was the establishment of the Office of the Director of Drug Control Policy. The Office of the National Drug Control Policy (ONCDP) is under the Executive Branch of government based out of the White House. The strategy of the ONCDP is to take a public health approach to drug abuse.36 The ONCDP includes special
