Policy Evaluation There are three areas to look at to gain an overall perspective if the war on drugs has been dented by PL 99-570: government, society, and academia. From a governmental perspective, the war on drugs is being fought with political bureaucracy and judicial backing. This is evident with the Drug Free Workplace Act of 198840 and high profile court cases that support the 1986 law.41 The government’s stance was that the war on drugs is working, which was held until 2008 when (then) Senator Joe Biden presented at the hearing on the “Federal Cocaine Sentencing Laws: Reforming The 100:1 Crack Powder Disparity.”42 He now involved the government into what society has felt like all along, that the war on drugs is not working well.43 Society has long felt that the war has been lost. Most would say that legalizing drugs would be a good thing; like in 2008 when Jeffrey Miron, an economist at Harvard suggested that legalizing drugs “would inject $76 billion into the US economy.”44 In January of this year the Wall Street Journal ran an article questioning whether the war has been lost concluding that decriminalization of drugs is necessary and that a paradox between increased government intervention and increased drug prices/risks exists.45
