Finally, academia has waged in evening the playing field to say that dents have been made but the war is not yet ready to be called. In a 2009 American Economic Association article, the authors argued that prevention and treatment are the top two priorities in the war on drugs however most government spending goes towards enforcement – while stating that the DEA did (at one point) create a reduction of methamphetamine supply by 50% in 1995.46 Another article also echoes that of the West Encyclopedia of law regarding racial disparity in relation to illegal drugs that the black community is “disproportionately affected by the consequences of drug-law enforcement strategies…because the minority poor are too often concentrated in hyper poor communities….[yet] any law enforcement policy must be attentive to the racial character of the special distribution of punishment…to ensure that it does not further damage the already weak social fabric of embattled neighborhoods.”47 Dam Baum writes “it is not accident that the first women prosecuted for prenatal drug abuse was black” and pointed out that when the ONDCP was established Bennett’s staff was “all white, all male [and] none with law enforcement or social service experience.”48
Conclusion Richard Schroeder was on to something when he said “the drug scene is constantly changing, but the central fact of drug use and drug abuse remains…when a nation sets unrealistic goals for itself, it invites failure, in turn, leads to frustration and social disintegration. Our problem with drug abuse is really a problem with people. We have spent vast sums of money fighting inanimate chemical substances when we should concentrate our efforts on helping warm bodied human beings.”49 There are many avenues of drug abuse prevention, treatment, regulation, and education available today. Joe Biden began the discussion in 2008 understanding that the laws need to be changed. PL 99-570 at the heart was a well needed insert into the drug abuse challenge in America in the 1980’s however it was pushed through too quickly and with other political agendas than just for the greater good. What is apparent is that the law has accomplished four things: first, it has been, and continues to be, a successful deterrent that helps reduce drug abuse, while taking drug-criminals off the street;50 secondly, has created much controversy as to its long-term validity; thirdly, provided some necessary laws pivotal to our economic stability (money laundering laws);51 and lastly, (and to this author the most important) has provided a vehicle for the discussion of and about drug abuse.
