APPENDIX: Author Interview
Below is an excerpt from a person interview between the author and Jeanne Obert, a licensed MFT/MSM, founder and board chair of Matrix Institute on Addictions based out of Los Angeles, CA. Jeanne was the clinical counselor for the primary subject in the October 1986 LIFE Magazine article entitled “Hooked on Hell.” Jeanne was nice enough to take time to answer a few questions that demonstrates a professional opinion of someone on one side of the drug war since the early 1980’s.
SL: Since you seem to have been in the fold since the inception of the drug act is 86 (which is when enforcement seemed to really begin to take a more public role) here are a few questions I have:
How do you think drug abuse has changed over the past 25 years? Is it more mainstream? Is it more acceptable in certain circles?
JO: I think that as the baby boomers move into their later years, the views of MJ abuse are getting more lenient. Generally I think, and hope, that people are beginning to think of substance abuse as a chronic relapsing condition akin to high blood pressure, diabetes, etc. That has been our goal.
SL: Do you think that there is still a need for drug and alcohol abuse counseling? JO: Absolutely - but using evidence-based interventions rather than 12 step recovering people suggesting others do as they did.
SL: From the 1986 LIFE article (I understand if it is patient confidentiality) do you know if those two men are still alive? Are they still addicts or did they overcome their addiction? JO: Last I heard Mike is still alive and doing well. Don't know about the other person. I still feel bad today about the way that article was published and how Mike's relapse was exploited. I learned a lesson from it all.
SL: What do you believe was the impetus for the 86 drug law? Crack? Len Bias' death? Other factors? JO: There is always the push-pull of demand reduction and crack down on supply. We historically vacillate between them. Somewhere in the middle is probably the most effective course of action.
SL: What do you think has been the biggest improvement on the war on drugs and what has been the biggest flop (from your professional stance)? JO: It is not a war we will ever win. Too much money and profit to be made. Increased awareness is the biggest improvement - trying to fight the war with penalties is the biggest mistake (along with scare tactics for kids).
Back to the movement toward viewing addiction as a real disease and finding ways to interrupt the disease process earlier and develop better tools (biopsychosocial) with which to treat people who might develop, are developing or have the disease.
SL: Thank you.
